          <section class="prose" aria-label="theory">
            <h2>How the Atbash cipher works</h2>
            <p>The Atbash cipher is one of the oldest known substitution ciphers. It simply reverses the alphabet:</p>
            <div class="formula-box mono text-sm">
              Plain:  ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ<br>
              Cipher: ZYXWVUTSRQPONMLKJIHGFEDCBA
            </div>
            <p>So:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>A ↔ Z</li>
              <li>B ↔ Y</li>
              <li>C ↔ X</li>
              <li>...</li>
              <li>M ↔ N</li>
            </ul>
            <p>This mapping is involutive, meaning that applying it twice gets you back the original message. That’s why the same tool can be used for both encoding and decoding.</p>
            <h3>Is Atbash secure today?</h3>
            <p>No. Atbash offers <strong>zero real cryptographic security</strong> by modern standards. Anyone who knows the method or even just suspects a simple substitution can reverse it immediately. Use it for fun, puzzles, ARGs, or educational demonstrations.</p>
          </section>
